                              <depth>0.100</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>185</height>
                              <width>112</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>

                        <foliation>Unfoliated.</foliation>
                        <collation> Quaternions throughout. 20IV-1(159). <catchwords>Catchwords
                              throughout most of the lower-left corners of the b
                           sides.</catchwords></collation>


                        <condition>Text in good condition.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>


                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="13" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 13
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in clear black
                        nasta‘līq with red subheaders. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus>final right flyleaf b side
                        (ivb)</locus> signed <q><persName role="fmo ins ato">W.
                        Woodhouse</persName>.</q>
                     <lb/>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> numbered <q>Nº 10</q> at
                     top-right and signed underneath <q><persName role="fmo ato ins">A.
                           Bagley</persName>, <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1855-07-19">19 July
                           1855</date></q><lb/>
                     <label>Bookplate and label:</label> the <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left paste-down</locus> bears the <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> bookplate with shelf mark <q xml:lang="en"
                        >2/I</q>, and label with class mark <q xml:lang="en">Persian 937</q>. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Contemporary hybrid British-Indian style binding from the <origPlace
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</origPlace>.</p>
                        <p>Endpapers of hand-dyed red paper stiff-leaved to British-made flyleaves,
                           with ~20 laid lines per 20 mm and 24 mm. between chain lines, watermarked
                           with an <watermark>heart-shaped VEIC (<orgName role="asn"
                                 ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/239176400" key="person_239176400">East
                                 India Company</orgName>) insignia</watermark>, dated <date
                              calendar="#Gregorian" when="1808">1808</date>:<lb/>
                           <label>Watermark:</label> (probable dimensions derived from Persian MS
                           263)): <dimensions type="watermark" unit="mm">
                              <height>128</height>
                              <width>58</width>
                           </dimensions><lb/>Counter marked: <q xml:lang="en"><watermark>S. Wise
                                 &amp; Patch</watermark></q>, of <persName role="ppm"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/99168840917045402115"
                              key="person_99168840917045402115">Stacey Wise (1783–1842)</persName>
                           in partnership with <persName role="ppm"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/81168840838645402128"
                              key="person_81168840838645402128">Christopher Patch (fl. 19th
                              c.)</persName> who then operated the Padsole Mill in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011704" key="place_7011704"
                              >Maidstone, Kent</placeName>.<lb/>
                           <label>Countermark:</label><dimensions type="countermark" unit="mm">
                              <height>17</height>
                              <width>170</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <p>Sewn all-along on two raised cords, laced into
                              <material>pasteboards</material>. Edges trimmed, spattered red, and
                           chevron endbands of yellow and metallic silver threads twined at <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                              >tail</locus>, the former now lost. Covered in full, highly polished
                           brick-red goatskin <material>leather</material>, tight-backed and
                           tight-jointed, with squares along the edges, and a flap (Type II binding
                           per Déroche).</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> panels
                           ruled with double silver lines. Boards decorated with scalloped central
                           mandorlas, with smaller ones above and below, flanked by vertical
                           cartouches and cornerpieces for the interior margins, engaved with
                           floraiate scrollwork designs, and exterior margins of a narrow floriate
                           chain design, all blocked in <material>gold</material>, with the same
                           replicated on the flap.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>234</height>
                              <width>174</width>
                              <depth>37</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In poor but stable condition, with
                           extensive losses caused by rodents along the head and fore-edge of the
                           boards and flap interiors and exteriors. Losses to exterior decoration.
                        </condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin change="#fix-dates">Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace>, undated but after <origDate calendar="#Gregorian"
                        notBefore="1806" notAfter="1810">circa 1806–1810</origDate> as per the dated
                     watermarks.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Previously owned by one <persName role="fmo ins ato">W.
                           Woodhouse</persName> as per his signature on the <locus>final right
                           flyleaf b side (ivb)</locus>, and <persName role="fmo ato ins">A.
                           Bagley</persName> as per his inscription on folio <locus from="1a"
                           to="1a">1a</locus>, dated <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1855-07-19"
                           >19 July 1855</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by barrister and <orgName>Royal Asiatic
                           Society</orgName> librarian <persName role="fmo seal ins"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/56966054/" key="person_56966054">William Hook
                           Morley (1815–1860)</persName> from an unidentified
                     source.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Morley's death, London bookseller <persName type="standard"
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225"
                           >Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold it, one of nine oriental
                        manuscripts, on behalf of his executors to <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> on <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1867-01-17">17 Jan. 1867</date> for £1. Note
                        this volume does not appear in Morley's prior sale catalogue.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                           >1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           type="corporation" role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John
                           Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
